issue_body:
### systemd version the issue has been seen with

254

### Used distribution

buntu 23.04

### Linux kernel version used

6.2.0-37-generic

### CPU architectures issue was seen on

aarch64

### Component

journalctl

### Expected behaviour you didn't see

If the system clock goes backward while journal entries are being created, those entries may not be found by `sd_journal_seek_realtime_usec()`[1].

For example,

If the system time goes backward like this.

```
sudo journalctl --vacuum-time=1s
<wait for a while to clear up journal>

date -s "<backward-time>"

date -s "<forward-time>"
```


Journal entries are

```
{
        "MESSAGE_ID" : "39f53479d3a045ac8e11786248231fbf",
        "MESSAGE" : "Started Time & Date Service.",
        "__REALTIME_TIMESTAMP" : "1699839632179843",
        "_SOURCE_REALTIME_TIMESTAMP" : "1699839632179536",
}

---Backward Begin
{
        "_SOURCE_REALTIME_TIMESTAMP" : "1699839632004914",
        "MESSAGE" : "Clock change detected. Flushing caches.",
        "__REALTIME_TIMESTAMP" : "1699839632005117",
}
...
{
        "__REALTIME_TIMESTAMP" : "1699839632056655",
        "MESSAGE_ID" : "c7a787079b354eaaa9e77b371893cd27",
        "MESSAGE" : "Changed local time to Mon 2023-11-13 01:40:32 UTC",
        "_SOURCE_REALTIME_TIMESTAMP" : "1699839632018027",
}
---End of backward
{
        "__REALTIME_TIMESTAMP" : "1699839662049861",
        "MESSAGE_ID" : "7ad2d189f7e94e70a38c781354912448",
        "_SOURCE_REALTIME_TIMESTAMP" : "1699839662049794",
        "MESSAGE" : "systemd-timedated.service: Deactivated successfully.",
}
```


### Unexpected behaviour you saw


Then, this may be failing.

```
     uint64_t curTs = 1699839632005117UL;
    sd_journal* journal;
     int ret = sd_journal_open(&journal, SD_JOURNAL_LOCAL_ONLY);
     ret = sd_journal_get_realtime_usec(journal, &curTs);
```

Is this a limitation of `sd_journal_get_realtime_usec()` - as the journal needs to be timely-sorted?




### Steps to reproduce the problem

```
sudo journalctl --vacuum-time=1s
<wait for a while to clear up journal>

date -s "<backward-time>"

date -s "<forward-time>"
```

Get journal output as json-pretty

```
$ journalctl -o json-pretty > js.out
```

Find the entry whose time goes backward

```
{
        "_RUNTIME_SCOPE" : "system",
        "MESSAGE" : "Clock change detected. Flushing caches.",
        "SYSLOG_IDENTIFIER" : "systemd-resolved",
....
        "__REALTIME_TIMESTAMP" : "1701754200000785",
        "_SYSTEMD_SLICE" : "system.slice",
        "_BOOT_ID" : "5c30ffc3d8ab4c2a8ea1be0f32001872",
        "_SOURCE_REALTIME_TIMESTAMP" : "1701754200000446",
...
        "_CMDLINE" : "/lib/systemd/systemd-resolved",
        "TID" : "582",
        "__MONOTONIC_TIMESTAMP" : "6517497947",
....
}
```

It may fail with `1701754200000785`.

$ test-realtime-seek 1701754200000785
 input TS=1701754200000785
sd_journal_seek_realtime_usec with timestamp=1701754200000785 is failing with r=0





### Additional program output to the terminal or log subsystem illustrating the issue

```sh
Test program: test-realtime-seek.c

#include <assert.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <systemd/sd-journal.h>

/* Compile: gcc test-realtime-seek.c -lsystemd */

int main(int argc, const char *argv[]) {
  sd_journal *j;
  sd_id128_t boot_id;
  int r;

  uint64_t ts = 0;

  char *end;
  ts = strtoull(argv[1], &end, 10);
  printf(" input TS=%lu\n", ts);

  r = sd_journal_open(&j, SD_JOURNAL_LOCAL_ONLY);
  assert(r >= 0);
  r = sd_journal_seek_realtime_usec(j, ts);
  if (r < 0) {
    printf("sd_journal_seek_realtime_usec with timestamp=%lu is failing with "
           "r=%d\n",
           ts, r);
    return 1;
  }

  for (uint64_t i = 0; i <= 5; i++) {
    sd_journal_next(j);
    uint64_t curTs = 0;
    r = sd_journal_get_realtime_usec(j, &curTs);
    if (r < 0) {
      printf("sd_journal_seek_realtime_usec with timestamp=%lu is failing with "
             "r=%d\n",
             ts, r);
      return 1;
    }
    if (curTs == ts) {
      printf("sd_journal_seek_realtime_usec with timestamp=%lu is successful\n",
             ts);
      return 0;
    }
  }
  printf(
      "sd_journal_seek_realtime_usec with timestamp=%lu is failing with r=%d\n",
      ts, r);

  return 1;
}
```
